Threats come from all areas, from malware attacks to compromised user credentials, and even accidental data leaks caused by human error. Naturally, it follows that an effective security system should have tools to cover all these areas.

Using tools like Azure Active Directory and Single Sign On, you can protect your system from common user credential problems while Azure Information Protection can keep your data encrypted and secure even if it's shared outside of your system.

We the Cyber-security team at Sahara Net understand the security problems facing your business are far from simple, which is why our multifaceted solution contains tools to address each one.

Are you an aspiring developer whether it be at Uni or a Boot camp? Would you like to find out more about life at Xero?Are you free on June 3 at 1pm NZST? 

Yes? Well, we have the perfect event for you!

Code with Xero is your chance to get some insight into the more technical side of things at Xero. 

First, we'll take you through who we are as a company and what we do. Then we will get into talking about version control, GIT, our front end tech stack (HTML, CSS, React, tooling and testing) and our back end stack (SQL, .Net/C#, API's, tooling and testing).

We'll even attempt a demo or two! Hope to see you online - you can register via the link below:

With the demand for video interviews going through the roof, we have rolled out some powerful features to our technical video interviewing platform.

1. Evaluation parameters - Structured interviews are seeing increased adoption and we now support defining evaluation parameters on which each candidate has to be scored after the interviews - hence allowing you to conduct structured interviews.

2. System Design interviews - We all know how hard it can be conduct system design interviews even on a video call. We heard your feedback and we have integrate Draw .io that allows you to create block diagrams and architecture design in a live interview.

3. Multiple interviewers - We heard your requests and have increased the number of interviewers from 3 to 5. Up to 5 interviewers can be part of the same interview. This is great for scenarios where you want to do pair programming, shadow interviews, or conduct an interview in a panel.

Read more in the blog post link in comments.

When was the last time you learnt something?

Whether it be professional or personally, goals are set in pursuit of solving a problem. The only way to solve that problem is through learning and growth. 

I used to think that some tasks could only be done by the experts, and that there was no point for me to spend time trying to learn something I didn‚Äôt even know existed.

So, when the need for a new app for my customers emerged, I reached out to an expert in the field.  Unfortunately, I wasn‚Äôt impressed by the service offered and so the journey began; I decided to learn how to do it myself.

In half of the time quoted by the expert, I had learnt coding, and I had a prototype that worked. Now, it wasn‚Äôt easy, but the more I learnt, the more I realised how beneficial this would be for me in the long run. And most of all, I get to improve the prototype to my customer requirements before starting building a scalable product.

How did I learn these things? By motivation and reading ‚Äòthe manual‚Äô. Failure is often part of the journey but acquiring knowledge is advantageous for both your professional and personal life.

What change are you going to make today? You might surprise yourself and learn something üòä

An interview is probably the one thing that will survive across time for choosing the right candidates for jobs and as the Covid-19 pandemic throws traditional interviewing practices out the window. 

We at HackerEarth have recently expanded the capabilities of our FaceCode live interview tool to ensure that our clients can keep hiring with confidence no matter the situation. Here are a few key takeaways from the latest release,

1. Evaluation parameters - Structured interviews are seeing increased adoption and we now support defining evaluation parameters on which each candidate has to be scored after the interviews.

2. System Design interviews - We all know how hard it can be to conduct system design interviews even on a video call. We heard your feedback and we have integrated Draw .io that allows you to create block diagrams and architecture designs.

3. Multiple interviewers - We heard your requests and have increased the number of interviewers from 3 to 5. This is great for scenarios where you want to do pair programming, shadow interviews, or conduct an interview in a panel.

Check out the link in the comments for the full post.

Flutter is updating the release process.
Starting with the April release of Flutter, it is moving to a branching model with a stabilization period for beta and stable releases. It will now branch at the beginning of the month for a beta release and stabilize this release by cherry-picking any critical fixes. Roughly once a quarter, the current beta branch will be promoted to the stable release. Flutter infrastructure now supports testing against branches. Learn more at https://bit.ly/3cwTz1y

Based on what other nations are experiencing at this moment, we must be prepared for second, third, and fourth waves of this infection. 

Unfortunately, beating this disease is harder than most would think. For us to beat it, we must first be sufficiently scared of it - it could happen to you, or anyone in your family. 

Then comes the necessity of good hygiene and proper precautions against this virus. These are a must if we have to break the chain of transmission and thus flatten the curve.

And finally here is something which must not be missed - the only defence you have against a viral disease is your immune system. Doctors and medicines are also only helping the immune system do its job. The vaccine also only serve as a learning experience for the immune system.

Thus it is very important that one and all maintain their health. Eat good food, get good exercise, and stay sane.

Difficult times call for difficult measures. Maybe it's time to think about putting safety measures that we never have before.

Phishing attempts have increased tremendously due to the COVID-19 crisis, and many of them reach the endpoint because remote employees are lacking the walls of security they had in-office. Maybe it's time we refrain from emails temporarily. Maybe it's time to block all emails with attachments or links. There are other ways we can communicate for the time being. Safety should be our number one concern.

For any CISOs out there that may be wondering how to go forward, recognize that your safety precautions put in place at the beginning of the year are gone. 2020 is a whole new ball game. Let's rebuild our roadmap together!

Check out my new eBook for a new CISO Roadmap. It's free!

Social Distancing Analyser
==================

According to WHO, at least 1 metre (3 feet) distance between persons are must to reduce the spread of corona virus (COVID-19). To analyse Social distancing in a public places and carry out necessary actions to better deal with the pandemic, I developed a model which can analyse social distancing parameters by detecting distance between two persons.

This is just a demo applied on a small video, I got to learn a lot with this project. Hope you will like it.

I was born into poverty where clean water was a luxury. But ever since I could remember, I‚Äôve always known that I could be and do whatever I set my mind to.

I struggled with self-worth after loosing my parents. I thought doing good in school would boost my worthiness and be more significant to the people around me, which I craved. I would skip lunch to study, taking night classes (most of the time I would pay for the classes with the money I earned from recycling because I didn‚Äôt wanted to bother my aunt). üíª Data Structures and Algo - Day 1:

What are Data Structures? They are nothing but a bunch of Uhaul boxes, movers, trucks and storage units trapped in a computer. 

All we are doing is to define, move, manipulate and manage these boxes. They often move from one place to another. Data is a nomad.

The simple logic is: first, we define a data structure (i.e. Uhaul medium box), then, organize/manipulate the data (i.e. insert your office supplies in the box), then return the data (your Uhaul box is ready to go). 

Insert, search, remove are sample examples of operations we can perform on data structures (after you think you packed all the office supplies, you find a keyboard laying around, and you open the Uhaul box to insert it). The type of the data structure (i.e. Uhaul box), will define what operations we can do with it. Not all are the same. There are also relationships between data structures, for example: kitchen related Uhaul boxes all belong to ‚Äúkitchen‚Äù,  office related Uhaul boxes all belong to ‚Äúoffice‚Äù etc.  

*U-Haul is an American moving equipment and storage rental company.

Can you think of a data structure from a daily life?

Several years ago, I found myself disillusioned with software engineering, so I explored a career shift.  I'd become fed up with the long hours in front of the monitor, the "nerd status", and the buggy lines of unmaintained code that littered the industry.  It seems sooner or later, every programmer faces a question of whether to continue coding or explore another path... I've seen numerous of my own colleagues gone off to become bartenders, restaurant owners, or live on a farm.  Having saved enough, I myself went
